receptor activation by converting cortisol to inactive cortisone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["11 alpha-hydroxylase","11 beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase","17 alpha-hydroxylase","21-hydroxylase","3 beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe enzyme \u003Cstrong\u003E11 beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase\u003C/strong\u003E type 2 (11\u03b2-HSD2) converts cortisol to cortisone in aldosterone-sensitive tissues like the kidney. This prevents cortisol from inappropriately activating mineralocorticoid receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are all steroidogenic enzymes with different roles:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E11 alpha-hydroxylase\u003C/strong\u003E converts 11-deoxycortisol to cortisol in the adrenal cortex\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E17 alpha-hydroxylase\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in both cortisol and androgen synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E21-hydroxylase\u003C/strong\u003E converts progesterone to deoxycorticosterone in mineralocorticoid synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E3 beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase\u003C/strong\u003E converts pregnenolone to progesterone early in steroidogenesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWithout 11\u03b2-HSD2, the much higher circulating levels of cortisol would constantly activate mineralocorticoid receptors, disrupting sodium and potassium homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["11 beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase type 2 converts cortisol to inactive cortisone in aldosterone-sensitive tissues to prevent inappropriate mineralocorticoid receptor activation.","This enzyme protection mechanism allows selective aldosterone binding to mineralocorticoid receptors despite higher circulating cortisol levels.","Cortisol circulates at 1000-fold higher concentrations than aldosterone in the bloodstream."],"references":["Chapman K, Holmes M, Seckl J. 11\u03b2-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenases: intracellular gate-keepers of tissue glucocorticoid action. Physiol Rev. 2013 Jul;93(3):1139-206. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00020.2012. PMID: 23899562; PMCID: PMC3962546.","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56496"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15647"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56496"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T19:01:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T19:02:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8338"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71025"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups",